SIMPLE: escape
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Escape
<hw>Es*cape"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Escaped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Escaping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>escapen</ets>,
<ets>eschapen</ets>, OF. <ets>escaper</ets>, <ets>eschaper</ets>, F.
<ets>echapper</ets>, fr. LL. <ets>ex cappa</ets> out of one's cape or
cloak; hence, to slip out of one's cape and escape. See 3d
<er>Cape</er>, and cf. <er>Scape</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To flee from and avoid; to be saved or exempt from; to shun; to
obtain security from; <as>as, to <ex>escape</ex> danger</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Sailors that <xex>escaped</xex> the wreck.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To avoid the notice of; to pass unobserved by; to
evade; <as>as, the fact <ex>escaped</ex> our attention</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>escaped</qex> the search of the enemy.</q>
<rj><qau>Ludlow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Escape</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Escape
<hw>Es*cape"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To flee, and become
secure from danger; -- often followed by <xex>from</xex> or <xex>out
of</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Haste, for thy life <qex>escape</qex>, nor look behind<?/<?/</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To get clear from danger or evil of any form; to be
passed without harm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such heretics . . . would have been thought fortunate, if they
<qex>escaped</qex> with life.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To get free from that which confines or holds; --
used of persons or things; <as>as, to <ex>escape</ex> from prison, from
arrest, or from slavery; gas <ex>escapes</ex> from the pipes;
electricity <ex>escapes</ex> from its conductors.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>escape</qex> out of these meshes.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Escape</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Escape
<hw>Es*cape"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of fleeing
from danger, of evading harm, or of avoiding notice; deliverance from
injury or any evil; flight; <as>as, an <ex>escape</ex> in battle; a
narrow <ex>escape</ex></as>; also, the means of escape; <as>as, a fire
<ex>escape</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would hasten my <qex>escape</qex> from the windy storm.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. lv. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which escapes attention or restraint; a
mistake; an oversight; also, transgression.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I should have been more accurate, and corrected all those former
<qex>escapes</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sally.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Thousand <xex>escapes</xex> of
wit.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The unlawful permission, by a
jailer or other custodian, of a prisoner's departure from
custody.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant which has escaped from
cultivation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Escape</xex> is technically distinguishable from
<xex>prison breach</xex>, which is the unlawful departure of the
prisoner from custody, <xex>escape</xex> being the permission of the
departure by the custodian, either by connivance or negligence. The term
<xex>escape</xex>, however, is applied by some of the old authorities to
a departure from custody by stratagem, or without force.</note>
<rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>An apophyge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Leakage or outflow, as of steam or a
liquid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>Leakage or loss of currents from
the conducting wires, caused by defective insulation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Escape pipe</b></col> <fld>(Steam Boilers)</fld>, <cd>a
pipe for carrying away steam that escapes through a safety valve.</cd>
-- <col><b>Escape valve</b></col> <fld>(Steam Engine)</fld>, <cd>a
relief valve; a safety valve. See under <er>Relief</er>, and
<er>Safety</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Escape wheel</b></col>
<fld>(Horol.)</fld>, <cd>the wheel of an escapement.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Escapement</ent>⟦br⟧
